<subSubSection pageId="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1648,1998]" pageId="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1829,1854]" pageId="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Externally, adults of the new species resemble many other Andean 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrank" authorityYear="1802" box="[1085,1190,1829,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1085,1190,1829,1853]" italics="true" pageId="3">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species as possessing fascia on forewing but differ from these species in the grey, silvery glossy collar. In the male genitalia, the combination of two very large apical processes of valva, a very long vinculum (
<figureCitation box="[1071,1156,1901,1926]" captionStart="FIGURES 46 – 53" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[162,1428,197,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[153,1433,195,1921]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 46 – 53. Male genitalia of Stigmella scutellariae Remeikis &amp; Stonis, sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide RA 653 (ZMUC). 46 – 50, capsule without phallus; 51 – 53, phallus (ZMUC)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1035620/files/figure.png" pageId="3">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
), triangular processes of transtilla, and a stout uncus distinguishes 
<taxonomicName authority="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Diškus &amp; Forero &amp; Torres, 2017" authorityName="Stonis &amp; Remeikis &amp; Diškus &amp; Forero &amp; Torres" authorityYear="2017" box="[628,875,1937,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellariae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[628,875,1937,1961]" italics="true" pageId="3">Stigmella scutellariae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[884,975,1936,1961]" pageId="3" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[884,975,1936,1961]" pageId="3">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schrank" authorityYear="1802" box="[1151,1256,1937,1961]" class="Insecta" family="Nepticulidae" genus="Stigmella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1151,1256,1937,1961]" italics="true" pageId="3">Stigmella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The host plant 
<taxonomicName box="[151,377,1973,1997]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lamiaceae" genus="Scutellaria" kingdom="Fungi" order="Lamiales" pageId="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="volubilis">
<emphasis box="[151,377,1973,1997]" italics="true" pageId="3">Scutellaria volubilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also makes this species highly distinctive.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
